If the checkpoint is written before the projection has been applied, a crash between the two leaves the read model one event behind — on restart the subscription resumes past the unapplied event and the view is permanently wrong. Writing the checkpoint after a successful apply makes the at-least-once semantics safe: a crash replays the last event, and because projections are idempotent (or guarded by event position), the duplicate is absorbed. The rule is apply then record; never record then apply.

